The conclusion is that you simply shouldn&#39;t return 0 for any two string values, unless you want them to be treated as identical (in your case that seems to mean that they are `equal`). A simple way is to use a Comparator like this:

```
class CompareLength implements Comparator&lt;String&gt; {
    public int compare(String str1, String str2) {
        int result = Integer.compare(str1.legnth(), str2.length());
        if (result == 0) {
          result = str1.compareTo(str2);
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

