It&#39;s all a little ugly.  Ideally, I would have preferred to simply remove the System.exit code, but I do not have access to the 3rd party library&#39;s source code.

You&#39;re using the *ViewHolder* pattern, where instead of every item in the list having its own `View`, you have a small pool of them which get *reused*. When an item scrolls out of view, its ``ViewHolder`` can be used to display another item that&#39;s scrolling into view.

So that new item gets an old `ViewHolder`, which was used to display some other item, and has all its data displayed - text, images, whatever. You need to *update* all that, so it&#39;s displaying the correct data for the *new* item - which is what you&#39;re doing in `getView`, after the `if` section that creates a new `ViewHolder` if the pool needs another one.

----

It sounds like your pool has **2** `ViewHolder`s, *A* and *B*. So the first item in your list uses VH *A*, the second uses *B*, the third uses *A* again, the fourth *B*, and so on.

When you click the first item, which is displayed in *ViewHolder A*, the click listener fires, and does this (other stuff removed):

````
if(mediaPlayer.isPlaying()) {
    viewHolder.ivPlay.setImageResource(R.drawable.stop);
} else {
    viewHolder.ivPlay.setImageResource(R.drawable.play);
}
````

So *ViewHolder A updates its image* when you click. But remember, *that ViewHolder gets reused* so every item using *A* will show that image! The result is that the image *depends on which ViewHolder the item happens to display in*, not *the item itself*.

----

So you need to store some playing/stopped state *for the item*, and make the click listener *update that*. And when you set up the `ViewHolder` to display an item&#39;s details, text etc, *that&#39;s where you set the play/stop image* as appropriate.

Assuming there&#39;s only one item that can play at a time, you could just hold a &quot;now playing&quot; value:

````
// store the playing item (if any) in the top level of your adapter
VerseData nowPlaying = null;
````

In `getView()`, use `nowPlaying` to decide which icon to display

````
VerseData verseData = arrayList.get(position);
viewHolder.number.setText(verseData.getNumber());
...
if (verseData.equals(nowPlaying)) {
    viewHolder.ivPlay.setImageResource(R.drawable.play);
} else {
    // you -always- have to explicitly set the data -either way-,
    // so it always shows the correct image - if it was play before, this will fix it
    viewHolder.ivPlay.setImageResource(R.drawable.stop);
}
````

And then update the playing item in your click listener

````
if(mediaPlayer.isPlaying()) {
    // stopping the playing item - clear the &quot;now playing&quot; value
    nowPlaying = null
} else {
    // otherwise set it to this item - this means any old &quot;now playing&quot; value
    // will be replaced
    nowPlaying = verseData
}
// since something&#39;s changed, items will need to refresh (so they can update their
// displays with the code in getView(), including displaying the correct image)
notifyDataSetChanged()
````

That&#39;s the basics, you&#39;ll have to fit that in with the rest of your code, but hopefully it makes sense! The playing state is part of your *data*, it&#39;s something associated with your *items*. `ViewHolder`s are temporary and you shouldn&#39;t try to store item state in them (like setting an icon) because they&#39;re reused for different items, so they eithr get wiped clean, or show old state that&#39;s incorrect for the item it&#39;s displaying.

Btw, a [`RecyclerView`][1] is the modern way to do this *ViewHolder pattern*, and it&#39;s easier to work with - you have separate methods for creating a new VH, and setting its data for an item. Just in case you need to do this in future!


  [1]: https://developer.android.com/develop/ui/views/layout/recyclerview

